Dear Kearsarge Regional High School Families,
You are invited to join the administrative team for a town hall style meeting regarding the reopening of the high school on Tuesday, July 28th from 6 to 8pm. A Zoom link will be sent to all parent/guardian and student emails on Tuesday afternoon. Please use the mute microphone feature when you enter the zoom event. The chat function will be enabled for you to ask your questions. We apologize for the lateness of this notice, we are trying to get a presentation in before Thursday's School Board meeting. Should you not be able to attend, feel free to call the high school and ask to speak with Charles Langille.

post_text: A Kearsarge student helping out...the high school recently got an email from a community member who wanted to tell about a student who did a random act of kindness! Bailey C. '21 was at a local beach swimming when a floaty another swimmer was using popped and thousands of little styrofoam beads flew everywhere. Bailey, alongside some friends, jumped into action and started finding ways to collect the little styrofoam beads as he was concerned about wildlife eating the beads. Bailey came up with ways to use nets and hats to collect all the little beads and help this family clean up the mess. The onlooker was very impressed about Bailey's desire to help and keep a local beach clean. Cougars doing GREAT things, nice job Bailey!

High schoolers! It's time to pick up your awards, diplomas, and yearbooks! We would like to distribute these on June 29th from 8-4pm. You will come to the back doors of the gymnasium and we will have items bagged and ready to go for students. Please pull up to the back of the gymnasium and a staff member will assist you in securing your materials.

If you are unable to attend this pick up day, please email Ellie at ephyllides@kearsarge.org, to make alternative arrangements.

If you have any questions, please call 603-927-4261. Thank you and have a great summer!

post_text: The school year of 2019-2020 was like no other students had ever experienced. With the onset of the Covid-19 pandemic, stay at home orders, and the change to remote learning, the 9th Grade World Perspectives teachers at KRHS made changes to instructional and assessment practices to best support and engage students. These changes culminated with students completing a project focused on capturing the experiences of students during the pandemic and the importance of primary sources in the recording of history. Some examples of the student projects can be found below as a means to create a virtual "Time Capsule" of their work.

post_text:
Each year, KRMS comes together to recognize the outstanding achievements of our students for the KRMS Awards Ceremony. This year, given the circumstances, we are presenting the ceremony digitally. Given the challenges of remote learning and the interruption it caused to the school year, we have decided not to count the third and fourth quarters in the calculations.

While it is not the same as gathering together in the gym, we hope that you join us in celebrating the accomplishments of this wonderful group of young people and in wishing our eighth graders the best of luck as the transition to high school and beyond.

https://spark.adobe.com/video/NDMoZ5mvZizgv

post_text:
Friends of Sutton Central Elementary School PTO - Sutton, New Hampshire members have come up with a novel way of helping both local businesses AND families during this difficult economic time. People who have taken part, or wish to take part in the Caring Card Project can purchase a gift card from a participating local business. When a donor calls the local business they need to clarify that their purchase of a gift card is a "Caring Card." The business will then place the Caring Card aside until it is collected, and then the gift card will be passed along to a local family in need. So far, this project has raised over $1500 to assist local families and businesses! The participating businesses include:

Appleseed Restaurant and Catering - Bradford: 938-2100

Morgan Hill Bookstore - New London: 526-5850

Little Brother Burger Company - New London: 887-0196

Millstone at 74 Main - New London: 526-4201

Artisan's New London - New London: 526-4227

Bubba's Bar & Grille - Newbury: 763-3290

Dear KRSD Parents and Guardians,

Effective Wednesday April 8, 2020, all meals will be free to all students who attend
Kearsarge Regional School District. The State of New Hampshire approved a waiver
that allows the District to offer meals to all students free of charge. This waiver is only
for the current COVID-19 crisis.

Student lunches and breakfasts are available now and during the week of April 27,
2020. Lunches and or breakfast can be picked up at one of three school locations
between 11:30am and 1:00 pm or delivery services will be available at designated stops
in your area. The pick-up locations are Simonds Elementary School, New London
Elementary School and Kearsarge Regional Middle School.

To Order: Complete the form below (all questions are required to be completed).

Orders will need to be submitted by 9:00 AM for same day lunch or next day breakfast.
Breakfast for the next day will be delivered with the lunch on the preceding day. All
orders must be submitted using this form. One form may be submitted for each family.
http://bit.ly/3a1bdJt

post_text:
Dear Kearsarge Community,

Recognizing that our area Internet providers are working as quickly as possible to help families gain access to the Internet, this activity still does take some time to accomplish. Therefore, we have added additional Wifi access to the Internet from Simonds Elementary School in Warner to help support families awaiting Internet connectivity in their homes. This Wifi zone is in addition ot the current one located in the rear parking lot of the SAU office in New London.

The Internet may be accessed via Wifi connectivity in the Simonds parking lot area near the basketball court and multipurpose room area of the school. Access to the Internet from this connection is also subject to the responsible use policy monitoring software.

We hope this continues to help as we navigate these challenging days ahead!

Please do not hesitate to contact us if you need assistance.

post_text:
Dear Kearsarge Community,

While all major Internet providers in NH are now offering free Internet services to families in need, it may require a few days for that installation to occur. To help provide some support for remote learning, the District has installed an Internet accessible WiFi area to the public in the parking area to the rear of the SAU offices directly in front of the James House Preschool at 114 Cougar Court, in New London NH.

Those seeking Internet access may park in the rear of the SAU and utilize the Kearsarge "KLC Guest" Wifi connection. This area of connectivity should provide coverage to the parking area nearest James House with sufficient speed to support students until an Internet provider can support the family in their home.

Access to the Internet also is monitored by the District's Internet filtering software, and supports responsible use only.

We hope this provides some support for those families in need.

post_text: Simonds Kindergarten has spent the last month learning about maple sugaring as part of a project based learning unit. The children tapped trees, collected sap, tasted the sap, boiled the sap to turn it into syrup. They will finish their unit when students will enjoy pancakes and their very own maple syrup. Nick Clark came in and taught students about the tools used in making syrup, how the tree makes sap, and the importance of cold nights and warm days. Kalvin and Courtney Rogers invited us to their sugar shack to see how they run lines, collect sap and use an evaporator to make syrup.

The children tapped trees, collected sap, tasted the sap, boiled the sap to turn it into syrup. They will finish their unit when students will enjoy pancakes and their very own maple syrup. Nick Clark came in and taught students about the tools used in making syrup, how the tree makes sap, and the importance of cold nights and warm days. Kalvin and Courtney Rogers invited us to their sugar shack to see how they run lines, collect sap and use an evaporator to make syrup.

Dear Kearsarge Community,

To address any potential future need for a long-term closure of school as a result of COVID 19, the Kearsarge District will be cancelling school for students on Monday, March16, 2020. Staff will have a professional work day during which they will be preparing remote learning activities and lessons for students.

Students will return to classes on Tuesday, March 17, 2020 and schools remain open until additional guidance supports closure.

Thank you for your support.

post_text: Lili Baer, 11th grade, has been named to the New England Junior National Nordic ski team. She finished the Junior National Qualifying races in the top 15 U20/U18 skiers in all of New England and will now travel to Truckee, CA to compete in the 2020 US Ski and Snowboard Junior National Championships from March 8-14th. This is an amazing accomplishment for Lili and speaks to her dedication and commitment to training and improving her skiing. Congratulations!

post_text: My name is Lily Pelkey-Jacobson '20, I am a senior at Kearsarge Regional High School and for my senior project I have chosen to create an online newspaper for the school. This newspaper is completely student run, with adult advisors to supervise the content of the paper. My mission is to allow young writers and journalists to find their niche in a collaborative and constructive environment, while also producing something beneficial for the school community. I hope that this helps encourage students to become more vocal on issues and events pertaining to the high school, as well allowing them to be creative in their vocality. We plan to produce papers monthly, or bimonthly with specific content for the high school. Hope you enjoy!

As of 2:10pm on November 1st:
Good Afternoon

We have received word from the bus company that several roads throughout the district have been blocked or compromised by downed limbs or trees, some of which have created road closures. The bus company will be attempting to return each student to their normal drop off location in a timely manner, but in some instances road closures will not allow them to deliver children as normally planned. In those cases, students at the Elementary level will be returned to their school and administration will support contacting parents to arrange for pick up at that location. Middle and High School students will be returned to the Middle School, as the High School recently lost power and may not have it in time for the students' return.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we work to return students home today in a timely and safe fashion.

post_text: Project C.L.I.M.B. students summited 4,802 foot Mt. Moosilauke on Friday, October 18, for an overnight camping trip at Beaver Brook Shelter. With low temperatures and high winds, students protected their faces from fast moving graupel, tiny hail-like snow crystals, as they crossed the bald summit. The exposed alpine rocks and vegetation were encrusted in rime ice, creating a beautiful crystalline alpine zone. Students pitched tents before cooking a warm meal over cook stoves, laughing in the glow of headlamps, and sharing trip highlights. Seven first time CLIMBers mixed right in with the group, taking on group responsibilities like collecting water for boiling, carrying group tents and food, and keeping gear as dry as possible. We are looking forward to our next trip to Lonesome Lake Hut on November 15-17 and hope new members will continue to join our ranks!

Update as of 7:05am -
The District has been informed that multiple trees are down creating power outages to school buildings as well as creating unsafe road conditions for buses. We have also been informed that restoration of electricity to the buildings by the conclusion of the two-hour delay window is not likely. As such, the District will be moving from a two-hour delay to a FULL CANCELLATION of school today, Thursday, October 17, 2019. It will NOT be a Blizzard Bag day.

post_text: Project C.L.I.M.B. students canoed across beautiful Squam Lake on Saturday, September 21st for an overnight camping trip to Bowman Island. In 80 degree, sunshine, students paired up, practicing their paddle strokes. They pitched tents before paddling north to West Rattlesnake Mountain, where they enjoyed a panoramic view of Squam Lake's many islands and coves. After a sunset paddle back, students cooked a meal over cook stoves, played games, and shared highlights. Eight first time CLIMBers mixed right in with the group, taking on group responsibilities like creating portable water, carrying group food, and keeping gear as dry as possible. We are looking forward to our next trip to Mount Moosilauke on October 18-19 and hope new members will continue to join our ranks!

post_text: Sutton Central Schoolâ€™s after school program is looking to hire a part-time group leader. Our program has reached itsâ€™ maximum number of students who can participate in the program. Currently, we have a waiting list for students who would like to attend the program, but in order to do so we must have another staff member. Candidates must be 18 years of age, reliable transportation, have or be willing to obtain their First Aid and CPR certificate, and must complete a background check and fingerprinting. Our program is coordinated through the Boys & Girls Clubs of Central NH. The position would be 5 days a week from 2 pm to 6 pm. If you are interested or know anyone that is interested, please have them contact the Site Director Danika Rainie via email (drainie@centralnhclubs.org).
